instance (n : ℕ) : MeasurableSpace (WignerSpace n) := by
  infer_instance
```

Now we define the measure distribution for the Wigner matrix.
The measure is `ν` on the diagonal and `μ` on the off-diagonal.

```tactics
def wignerMeasureDist (n : ℕ) : Index n → Measure ℝ :=
  fun (p : Index n) =>
    if p.val.1 = p.val.2 then ν
    else μ
```

Now we define the probability measure on the Wigner space.
It is the product measure of the measures on the index set.

```tactics
noncomputable
def WignerMeasure (n : ℕ) : Measure (WignerSpace n) :=
  Measure.pi (wignerMeasureDist μ ν n)
```

Now we define the function that creates the matrix from the Wigner space element.
The function `wignerMatrixEntryFunction` defines the matrix entries based on the Wigner space element.

```tactics
@[grind, simp]
def wignerMatrixEntryFunction (ω : WignerSpace n) : (Fin n) → (Fin n) → ℝ :=
  fun i j =>
    if h_eq : i = j then
      ω (⟨(i, i), le_refl i⟩)
    else if h_lt : i < j then
      ω (⟨(i, j), le_of_lt h_lt⟩)
    else
      have h_gt : j < i := by
         apply lt_of_le_of_ne
         apply le_of_not_gt h_lt
         simp
      ω (⟨(j, i), le_of_lt h_gt⟩)
```

Now we define the Wigner matrix map and prove it is measurable.

```tactics
def wignerMatrixMap' (ω : WignerSpace n) : Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ :=
  Matrix.of (wignerMatrixEntryFunction ω)
```

Now we define the scaled Wigner matrix map and prove it is measurable.

```tactics
noncomputable
def wignerMatrixMapScaled (n : ℕ) : (WignerSpace n) → Matrix (Fin n) (Fin n) ℝ :=
  fun (ω : WignerSpace n) ↦ (1 / Real.sqrt (n : ℝ)) • (wignerMatrixMap' ω)
